Classical mechanics, electromagnetism, and thermodynamics are fundamental principles that are used in the analysis and understanding of celestial objects in astronomical science. Here is a brief overview of how each of these principles can be applied:
1. Classical mechanics: This principle is used to understand the motion of celestial objects, such as planets, moons, and asteroids. The laws of motion and gravity are used to calculate the trajectories of these objects and predict their future positions.
2. Electromagnetism: This principle is used to understand the behavior of electromagnetic radiation, such as light and radio waves, emitted by celestial objects. By studying the spectrum of this radiation, astronomers can determine the composition and temperature of these objects.
3. Thermodynamics: This principle is used to understand the energy transfer and heat flow within celestial objects. By studying the temperature and energy output of these objects, astronomers can gain insights into their internal structure and composition.
Here is a C++ code example that demonstrates how classical mechanics can be used to calculate the trajectory of a celestial object:
```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <cmath>
using namespace std;
const double G = 6.6743e-11; // gravitational constant
struct Vector {
    double x, y, z;
};
struct Body {
    Vector position, velocity, acceleration;
    double mass;
};
void calculateAcceleration(Body& body1, Body& body2) {
    Vector direction;
    double distance, magnitude;

    direction.x = body2.position.x - body1.position.x;
    direction.y = body2.position.y - body1.position.y;
    direction.z = body2.position.z - body1.position.z;

    distance = sqrt(pow(direction.x, 2) + pow(direction.y, 2) + pow(direction.z, 2));

    magnitude = G * body2.mass / pow(distance, 2);

    body1.acceleration.x += magnitude * direction.x / distance;
    body1.acceleration.y += magnitude * direction.y / distance;
    body1.acceleration.z += magnitude * direction.z / distance;
}
int main() {
    Body sun, earth;
    double timeStep = 86400; // 1 day in seconds
    double totalTime = 365 * timeStep; // 1 year in seconds

    // initialize sun
    sun.mass = 1.989e30; // mass of sun in kg
    sun.position.x = 0;
    sun.position.y = 0;
    sun.position.z = 0;

    // initialize earth
    earth.mass = 5.972e24; // mass of earth in kg
    earth.position.x = 1.496e11; // distance from sun in meters
    earth.position.y = 0;
    earth.position.z = 0;
    earth.velocity.x = 0;
    earth.velocity.y = 2.9783e4; // orbital velocity in m/s
    earth.velocity.z = 0;

    for (double time = 0; time < totalTime; time += timeStep) {
        // calculate acceleration of earth due to sun
        earth.acceleration.x = 0;
        earth.acceleration.y = 0;
        earth.acceleration.z = 0;

        calculateAcceleration(earth, sun);

        // update position and velocity of earth
        earth.position.x += earth.velocity.x * timeStep + 0.5 * earth.acceleration.x * pow(timeStep, 2);
        earth.position.y += earth.velocity.y * timeStep + 0.5 * earth.acceleration.y * pow(timeStep, 2);
        earth.position.z += earth.velocity.z * timeStep + 0.5 * earth.acceleration.z * pow(timeStep, 2);

        earth.velocity.x += earth.acceleration.x * timeStep;
        earth.velocity.y += earth.acceleration.y * timeStep;
        earth.velocity.z += earth.acceleration.z * timeStep;

        cout << "Time: " << time / 86400 << " days" << endl;
        cout << "Position: (" << earth.position.x << ", " << earth.position.y << ", " << earth.position.z << ")" << endl;
        cout << "Velocity: (" << earth.velocity.x << ", " << earth.velocity.y << ", " << earth.velocity.z << ")" << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```
This code calculates the trajectory of the Earth around the Sun using the laws of motion and gravity. It initializes the positions and velocities of the Sun and Earth, and then calculates the acceleration of the Earth due to the gravitational force of the Sun. It then updates the position and velocity of the Earth based on this acceleration and outputs the results for each day of a year.

