Network byte order is in big endian format, which means the most significant byte comes first. You can configure your `ByteBuffer` properly by setting the order using `ByteOrder#BIG_ENDIAN`. This ensures that the byte order is consistent with the network byte order.

Here is an example code snippet that demonstrates how to handle the conversion at the client side using `ByteBuffer`:

```java
import java.nio.ByteBuffer;
import java.nio.ByteOrder;

// Assuming you have received the block count as two bytes
byte byte0 = ...; // received byte 0
byte byte1 = ...; // received byte 1

// Create a ByteBuffer and set the order to big endian
ByteBuffer buffer = ByteBuffer.allocate(2);
buffer.order(ByteOrder.BIG_ENDIAN);

// Put the received bytes in the buffer
buffer.put(byte0);
buffer.put(byte1);

// Reset the position to the beginning of the buffer
buffer.flip();

// Retrieve the block count value as a short
short blockCount = buffer.getShort();

// Now you have the block count value in the original form
System.out.println("Block count: " + blockCount);
```

